Check out our latest vlog, link in bio :)', 'How was your July?', 'Reunited!', 'The finest pussy I seen all year', "Today is one of the most important days of my life.

1. We spent 10 days shooting and 2 weeks editing around the clock for what I believe to be the best client I ever worked with, producing 2 videos that I have never been prouder to show. Yes, I would say it's the best video I ever made (and I've made A LOT of videos). I edited over 3000+ videos over the last decade.

2. I would like to thank @klooksg for being the coolest client ever for taking the leap of faith with us even though we have no subscribers or followers. It is also the first time in my life as an editor that I had no changes to make.

3. I would like to thank my crew for toughing it out and working around the clock to make this happen. Especially @whitexsmoke for crashing on my sofa and working around the clock with me to deliver this video, and @bombiibii for putting up with my shit and whining and still trying to make the best of shituations

4. I would like to thank my girlfriend, @cherylenechan for taking care of me and making sure I didn't collapse on the table while editing and forgetting to go to the toilet or eat.

5. Last but not least, I would like to thank what little friends and fans I had left for sharing and supporting the video and supporting my comeback. It hasn't been easy, but as I mentioned before, all I ever wanted to do was make good videos with no drama, no shade, no tea, and no politics. That will be the direction of my new channel. We also won't be releasing videos on a schedule because I do wish for work-life balance. 

Let our work speak for us.

Link in bio

â€˜The more you try to be certain about something, the more uncertain and insecure you will feel.â€™

Seeking to control outcomes for things (relationships, getting accepted for that job) that are outside of our control would bring anxiety and impatience. Itâ€™s easy to look at something not going your way, and then let your anxiety create these crazy implausible branching narratives to believe the certainty of something not going your way.

This is because of a tendency to interpret your experience in a way that coheres to your previous experiences, feelings and beliefs. @xingweird helped me take this pic', 'Year 3 for me in NUS was an extremely tough time. I was riddled with anxiety, stemming from a failing relationship, worrying about a lack of direction of what I wanted to do (aka quarter-life crisis), felt like an imposter in the course I was in, and academic burnout (Computer Science is tough).

Up till that point I never really associated the idea of mental wellbeing with myself. Me, with mental health issues? No way. Only people that were clinically diagnosed could claim they had those issues. Well, that was what I thought.

Intense worry about the uncertainty of my future, feeling a sense of overwhelm and lack of control in my life due to school, constant fatigue and having trouble concentrating. A feeling of dread when it came to nighttime as I struggled to sleep; my head clogged up with thoughts and worries that plagued me throughout the day. These are all symptoms of general anxiety disorder.

You see my fellow students, you arenâ€™t as alone as you think you are. We are all one and the same in our feelings, even if our problems differ. You may think that the problem of you stressing to get an assignment done on time is inferior to that of someone else going through a heartbreak, thus invalidating your right to be anxious.

But itâ€™s not a competition of who has the biggest problem, where only the ones facing the most have the right to seek help for their mental health. All of us have our own problems. The right to your own feelings lies within yourself. It would be great if we could collectively start to acknowledge our own mental wellbeing, to realise that itâ€™s okay that we might have issues, and also to know that we arenâ€™t alone.

To help with that, NUS is organising K(NO)W Stigma 2022, an event centred around breaking the stigmas around mental wellness. Join them in a panel discussion that would help demystify the topic of mental wellness, as well as create a safe space for more in-depth dialogue surrounding mental health.

For more details, head to the @nus.hwb Instagram or Facebook page, and you can sign-up for the event through the link in my bio.

#NUSAreuOK #NUSKnowStigma2022', "Goodbye Sheares Hall, the place I could call a home for the past academic year.

A lesson I've learned about home: A dream home doesn't have to be a bungalow filled with swimming pools, bowling alleys, and more amenities than one could need. You don't need a penthouse, 10,000 square feet, or a balcony that stretches out far and wide. A home is a lot more than the superficial. It's a place of safety, security, comfort, and peace. A place you go to at the end of an exhausting day and immediately feel relaxed. A place without judgment, and where you can let your mind rest and be at ease. Even if that's a small little room at the corner of NUS.

I'm not someone that has a large amount of attachment to Sheares Hall as compared to some of my other graduating schoolmates. I didn't join many events or CCAs, nor have I really made a lot of friends that would honestly persist past this graduation from the hall. But I would be lying if I said that 3 of the 4 years I've stayed here haven't impacted me in a large way.

There are a few things I would miss. The peaceful and quiet nature of Pasir Panjang. Communal living with the few close friends I've taken away. The subtle chirping of birds nestled on the roof (although I won't miss the bird poop), and the gentle breeze that flows through the corridor of the rooftop floor that I stayed on. The idea of having the beautiful campus of NUS like my own backyard. The low-rise buildings nestled around the area, giving me an unobstructed view of the sky in its entirety. As you can tell, this allowed me to experience some magnificent sunsets over the past 10 months.

But what I will miss the most would be having this space I could call mine, even if it was just for a short 10 months. A place I could feel safe in, a space where I could do anything I wanted. A small little room where I could feel at peace. At home. And if this is a teaser of what owning my own place feels like, consider me motivated in wanting to achieve that sooner rather than later.

Goodbye Sheares. Thank you for the lessons learned, the people I've met, the tranquility you've given me, and the motivation you've sparked inside of me.", 'petition for power pose emoji', "Senior's farewell night in Sheares Hall, time for another WADIO

Thanks Aaron for asking me to show up at your party.', 'Iâ€™ve always said that the world is a different place for the heartbroken. It moves on a different axis, at a different speed. Time skips backwards and forwards fleetingly. The heartbroken might go through thousands of micro-emotions a day trying to figure out how to get through it without picking up the phone to hear that old familiar voice. In the land of heartbreak, moments of strength, independence, and devil-may-care rebellion are intricately woven together with grief, paralyzing vulnerability and hopelessness. Imagining your future might always take you on a detour back to the past. And this is all to say, that the next album Iâ€™ll be releasing is my version of Red.
 
Musically and lyrically, Red resembled a heartbroken person. It was all over the place, a fractured mosaic of feelings that somehow all fit together in the end. Happy, free, confused, lonely, devastated, euphoric, wild, and tortured by memories past. Like trying on pieces of a new life, I went into the studio and experimented with different sounds and collaborators. And Iâ€™m not sure if it was pouring my thoughts into this album, hearing thousands of your voices sing the lyrics back to me in passionate solidarity, or if it was simply time, but something was healed along the way.

Sometimes you need to talk it over (over and over and over) for it to ever really be... over. Like your friend who calls you in the middle of the night going on and on about their ex, I just couldnâ€™t stop writing. This will be the first time you hear all 30 songs that were meant to go on Red. And hey, one of them is even ten minutes long.

Red (Taylorâ€™s Version) will be out November 12.

SlaÃƒÃ…inte!', None, "Also, Iâ€šÃ„Ã´ve just found out that 'Waiting for the Barbariansâ€šÃ„Ã´, made with my dear friends Mark Rylance and Robert Pattinson, is out in the U.K. this week. Hope you guys get a chance to see it.", 'Hello All!
I just wanted to thank you all once again for your constant and loyal support throughout many long and interesting episodes of my life...
I am only here because of you â€šÃ„Ã® and Iâ€šÃ„Ã´m only here for you!!!

JD', 'Two months before the world was subjected to the shocking live coverage of the merciless, bloodthirsty and public daylight murder of JFK in Nov. 1963, Bob Dylan sat down to write a songâ€šÃ„Â¶ He had a particular idea in mind, which he recorded mere weeks before Kennedyâ€šÃ„Ã´s tragic Assassination. Dylan had already achieved stratospheric acclaim from his treasure-producing workmanship and poetic abilities. He had already jacked up the bar of songwriting to an untouchable level. He also became a reluctant prophet, which can be quite an occupational hazardâ€šÃ„Â¶Yet he remained himself while dodging all manner of con artists, bloodsuckers, angles, arrows, ignorance, injustices, and scrutinization of his life. His intentions remained pure. So he sat down and wrote the gold standard of protest songs, the seminal and most significant, mind boggling and staggeringly poetic, prophetic protest song the world will ever know: â€šÃ„ÃºThe Times They Are A-Changinâ€šÃ„Ã´â€šÃ„Ã¹. Dylanâ€šÃ„Ã´s song applies to Covid-19, it also, very strongly applies to the life altering image of George Floyd, forever seared to our brainsâ€šÃ„Â¶ For me, it applies to the moment we are in, it applies to the moment they were in in 1963, it applies to everything before and everything since and everything that will be. 
I chose to perform this song live, for my friend @drbarbarasturm Covid benefit several weeks agoâ€šÃ„Â¶ I didnâ€šÃ„Ã´t really know how to play it, but I figured Iâ€šÃ„Ã´d give it a shot, as it seemed to apply so well. And it applies now, more than ever. It was performed a couple of weeks before our collective paralysis was rendered complete by the images of our fellow human George Floyd being cruelly and brutally tortured to death on live TV.

Let us take a moment to remember the sacrificial hero George Floyd and look with hope towards the changes that his tragic death will cause. And letâ€šÃ„Ã´s salute the reluctant prophet Bob Dylan and the dream of change he inspired then, now, and onwardsâ€šÃ„Â¶ His impact is that of Shakespeare, Marlowe, Hunter Thompson, Marlon Brando, Woody Guthrie, William Blake, Picasso, Bach and Mozart. 
Dylanâ€šÃ„Ã´s song is to be kept near you, AT ALL TIMES!!! All love and respect,
JD', 'As the majority of American people, our global community and our extended family of humans helplessly watched a man die on televisionâ€šÃ„Â¶ I too, was exposed to the atrocity of blatant barbarism, \xa0ruthless cruelty and unmitigated lack of humanity. \xa0A handcuffed man, pleading for his life lay prone with the full weight of a man sworn to defend the peace on his neck. The victim of this heinous act of cowardice, George Floyd, told the officers that he could not breathe. As he called for his dead mother, how could our collective hearts not break as his face was ground and mashed firmly into the pavement by those sworn to protect him, and all of us? Justice, I desperately hope, will address the horror of Officer Chauvinâ€šÃ„Ã´s nonchalance and indifference to his participation in the agony, suffering and ultimately the murder of our fellow traveler George Floyd in a grotesque illustration of the abuse of power!!!
There is no way to make sense of what is senseless. There is no way to restore a life that has been taken. Just as there is no way to un-break a heart that is broken. 
What we can do is make a vow to ourselves that racism and the ignorance inherent in such judgmental ugliness that it gives birth to, is NO LONGER AN OPTION!!! THERE MUST BE A CHANGE!!! DEMAND IT!!!! My dear friend and brother, Killer Mike - (Run The Jewels), is a brilliant musician, artist, activist for social justice and the son of an Atlanta Policeman. He is also, one of the kindest, most caring and loving human beings that Iâ€šÃ„Ã´ve ever had the pleasure and honor to know!!! I beg everyone to listen to the remarks of this true statesman. True statesmen have never been so needed, and theyâ€šÃ„Ã´ve never been in such short supply. 
With All Love, 
JD', 'Itâ€šÃ„Ã´s odd, the things that we once gave such pure, intense focus and devotion to for months on end. Then suddenly the wind shifts and off we go on a new tack. And for far too long, these earlier interests or passions sadly fall by the wayside and recede into the vast recesses of some hoarderâ€šÃ„Ã´s crawlspace in the brain cloaked in heaps of the other things that my skull had no room forâ€šÃ„Â¶until recently. 
I found this painting, which I had started in 2006 â€šÃ„Â¶ for 14 years Iâ€šÃ„Ã´d never touched the painting â€šÃ„Ã¬ the occasional glance, at best. Yet it somehow always lingered in my mind, this piece of unfinished business. 
Even while we are forced to live in the immediate, some strange species of the interrupted passion that has been invested in an object we once focused on awaits our return from far away. I will keep you apprised of the progress! All Love,

* Women made up (only) 6% of all cinematographers working on the top 250 films of 2021.

#pradabeautypartner", None, "I didnâ€šÃ„Ã´t actually set out to start making films. Iâ€šÃ„Ã´d say the real beginning was taking in what I saw going on around me on set, & then starting to learn how to apply it in other parts of my life. For instance: my Mum nervously would be getting ready for her job interviews, & knowing I knew how to apply makeup after so many hours of watching other people do it in the makeup chair, we made it our ritual that I would do her face before any of her important occasions. 
Then filmmaking itself started by making love letters to my friends. Whether it was styling them, or producing photoshoots for their websites or headshots for their businesses - I loved helping out. Selfishly sometimes I also did it because I just wanted them to see all the beauty I saw in them that they never seemed to get. 
Then over time I started assisting a friend running sound on set. Then, very slowly I started working behind the camera (It hurt my back so much at first ï£¿Ã¼Ã²Ã‡). Then I got involved in editing. Now here I am, sharing my first go at directing something. 
I couldnâ€šÃ„Ã´t have done it without the friends I could be vulnerable enough with to show that I didnâ€šÃ„Ã´t know what I was doing & to ask for help from every step of the way. To these people (you know who you are) you have literally made a mark on my life & I hope I always get to make things WITH you. Thanks for believing in me. 
@emma_webstah this is my love letter to you. Also, I am a day late!:-( 

Not many people know what autism is, or what this entails, but to those who care, thank you.

HH (my brother) was diagnosed with autism at age 2. This was a huge blow to my family. My parents questioned: Why HH of all people? Why us? This is the case for most families whose kids are diagnosed with autism. 

Given that Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) was not well known 21 years ago as it is today, we worried about my brotherâ€šÃ„Ã´s development and ability to integrate into society. A society that wasnâ€šÃ„Ã´t forgiving, or accepting to those who did not seem â€šÃ„Ãºnormalâ€šÃ„Ã¹ ( for a lack of a better word ). Everyday, we worried about how HH was going to go to school; make friends; get a job; talk to people; be self sufficient: and the list goes on. The worries were endless. How could we cope with having a family member with ASD, when we ourselves didnâ€šÃ„Ã´t even know what ASD was? So, what is ASD?

ASD is a developmental disability that affects 1 in 150 children in ï£¿Ã¼Ã¡âˆï£¿Ã¼Ã¡Â¨, and it is generally seen as a different way of thinking. People with Autism often have problems with emotional, social and communication skills- which is why many people think of them as â€šÃ„Ãºweirdâ€šÃ„Ã¹, â€šÃ„Ãºlonerâ€šÃ„Ã¹, â€šÃ„Ãºeccentricâ€šÃ„Ã¹. 

But people with autism should not be defined solely by how they communicate, feel, or act. They just operate a little differently, and different is not necessarily bad. Different can be good. But not everyone thinks that way! And that begets the question: how can I be more accepting of someone who has autism? 

I donâ€šÃ„Ã´t think there is a right answer to this. You can find a way to do so that suits you! It will definitely not be easy, but please remember to be respectful, and get over prejudice & bias that you may have. It is not everyday you may meet someone with autism, but when you do, be kind. 

It has taken me & my family years, to learn how to cope and function with HH. The journey was difficult, and I do not think it will be easy for years to come. But I am grateful for everything HH has taught us- to be kind, patient, and loving.

Early last year in January 2021, I rushed myself to the A&E at a hospital near my home because I thought I had appendicitis/ Rhabdomyolysis due to sharp pains in my abdomen. An ectopic pregnancy is also fatal for the fetus as it cannot survive outside of the uterus.

today (yesterday) also marks just over a month following the death of a dude who was quintessential to this space.

no amount of consolation, catharsis, coping, vice, distraction, art, sappy songs, poetry, memorial, or pretty quotes about death can ever erase the tragedy and injustice of the loss of the boy with the kindest heart and the kindest smile, who deserved so much better from the world and the people in it. 

the essence of the surreal is something familiar in an unfamiliar context. it was beyond surreal to see a familiar bodyâ€šÃ„Ã® one we know, weâ€šÃ„Ã´ve touched, weâ€šÃ„Ã´ve seen move, we loveâ€šÃ„Ã® lying in a casket wearing unfamiliar clothes (a suit he would have protested), with an unfamiliar hairstyle (he also wouldâ€šÃ„Ã´ve protested), and a very unfamiliar wound just above the ear. a wound I canâ€šÃ„Ã´t get out of my head. 

there is something so surreal about loving someone that does not exist (particularly when they existed just a few moments ago).

there is something so fundamentally wrong with sending a friendâ€šÃ„Ã´s body into a furnace to burn. 

and now I realise how closely tied we are to spaces, whatever those spaces may be. because as time goes by, finnâ€šÃ„Ã´s absence from all these spacesâ€šÃ„Ã® figuratively (our group) and literally (this studio)â€šÃ„Ã® becomes increasingly clear and increasingly painful.

there is something so wrong with his absence from this world. and there is something so irreconcilable about his non-existence.

but as I grieve his death (and mourn a future that never will be), I also know I have no choice but to simultaneously celebrate his life, particularly on a day like today. and so we try and drink to him and remember good times, his laugh, his person, and his friendship. we pour whiskey at his memorial, and we keep a space open for him. we buy an extra beer. we remember what a fucking good person he was, and we try to let that goodness live through us. it doesnâ€šÃ„Ã´t bring him back and nothing can ever be the same, but itâ€šÃ„Ã´s the most we can do to preserve him.
